03/28/2023,748.2151(b)(1) - Medication,Medication,No,04/04/2023,04/03/2023,L:Medication,Medium High,Yes,"I observed a medication log to have a missing time for medication administration in the Laurence and Davis Cabin, and this medication log had been checked by three staff to ensure accuracy.",
12/29/2022,748.2151(c)(5) - Medication,Medication,No,01/12/2023,01/12/2023,L:Medication,Medium High,Yes,"Several of the medication logs reviewed did not indicate if the medication was administered during the morning or night.   In the Poston, the medication was documented as being administered at PM but the prescription is for morning medication.","The RTC programs will review the following procedures in staff meetings on January 11, 2023. The procedures will be effective January 15, 2023. 
Med admin in the AM will be double counted before being admin. The med will then be triple counted and checked for accuracy by our Crisis & Trauma Team to ensure all spaces are filled and signed in correctly. In addition, they will check that the med was prepped and admin properly. 
Med admin in the evening will be doubled counted before being admin.  In addition, they will check that the med was prepped and admin properly. The Campus Administrator for the day will triple count the med and ensure all spaces are filled and signed in correctly. 
The med log has been updated to provide more space for signatures, etc. This will allow for clearer documentation on the med logs. The updated med log will be effective Sunday, January 15, 2023.  We will replace the old forms and start the new forms when the RX drug form has been completed.
The following excerpt of RMYA's policies and procedures will be reviewed agency wide in staff meetings during the week of January 9, 2023. The policy referenced below is located in RMYAs manual, Part 9: Staff Procedures, G. Medical/Dental Care, #2, page 40: 

     Med Procedures
Meds will be admin as RX by the physician. Psychotropic meds are RX and monitored by the contracting psychiatrist, in accordance with guidelines established in the Psychotropic Med Utilization Parameters for Foster Children. When med is initially prescribed to a resident, the legal guardian will be notified and given a copy of the med evaluation as well as information on the recommended med regarding benefits, risks and other alternatives is available. Written consent from the legal guardian is obtained before any new med is started with any resident
      All  and non-RX med is to be kept double locked in a med cabinet in staff office at all times where access is limited only to program staff. All RX med is packaged and labeled with the following information:
 Residents name
 Med name
 Dosage
 Prescribing physicians name
 RX number or code identifying written order
Administering any drug samples to a resident without a RX is strictly prohibited.
   The staff is responsible for distributing RX and non-RX med when necessary and in accordance with instructions on the med. All staff authorized to admin med must have completed the necessary training in med control and admin as well as have knowledge of all applicable legal requirements. Program staff will observe and assess all residents for possible med side effects. The staff will consult with the On-call Nurse or other medical professional as necessary regarding side effects observed.
    A separate log is kept on each med RX. Information on the RX Drug Form should include:
  resident's full name
  name, strength, and dosage of med
  pharmacy name, address, and phone number
  prescribing physicians name
  RX number
  reason for administering med
  expiration date
  number of refills remaining
 A copy of each RXs formulary sheet should be maintained in the RX drug log. This sheet provides helpful information on possible side effects and possible interactions with other RX and non-RX meds.
   When administering meds, the staff should record the following information on the log using black or blue ink pen only:
  signature of staff administering med
  date (day, month, and year) and time the med was administered
  amount of med given
  balance of med remaining
  childs refusal to accept med, if applicable
Staff should ensure that med is taken by placing the med in the mouth, watching the resident swallow the med, and then checking his mouth and under his tongue to ensure it has been swallowed.
   Additionally, the employees involved in the errors in documentation, etc., will receive disciplinary action in the form of a write up which will be placed in their personnel file.   
"
