01/13/2021,748.3301(c) - Individual Standards Evaluated,Individual Standards Evaluated,No,03/10/2021,03/17/2021,Individual Standards Evaluated,Medium High,Yes,"During an emergency behavior intervention, a child in care was cut by a nail that was sticking out of the plexiglass. ","Compliance response from the administrator-(Covered in staff notes/meetings March 3-5th) All staff should be on the watch for safety issues and are responsible for putting in a maintenance ticket to have repair completed.  YES +, Program Managers, and Program Administrators should walk their programs daily with a critical eye, looking for both issues with cleanliness and safety hazards regarding doors, windows, flooring or walls and report any and all deficiencies to the facility maintenance department as a Licensing ticket request.  Their findings should be reviewed with their supervisors, and addressed with staff (if cleanliness) or with maintenance if a safety/maintenance issue.  Anything deemed an emergency/licensing should include a phone call to Joseph Rudolph (Sr. Director of Facilities and Food Service), as well as a maintenance ticket being submitted. Maintenance staff will respond to correct deficiencies that are considered minor safety issues within 24 hours.  Items that are considered major safety issues will be corrected within 4 hours by on-call maintenance staff. 

Facilities/maintenance staff conduct preventative maintenance (i.e. changing air filters, change batteries is smoke alarms, etc.) as well as complete items on their maintenance list sent in via the maintenance ticketing system on a regular basis.  Facilities staff should bring to attention any maintenance/safety concerns they observe that have not been submitted for repair, and request staff submit so task can be completed.  Facilities staff should also report to the Program Manager, Administrator or senior leadership, any concerns they have from a cleanliness perspective.

Facility maintenance staff will conduct a monthly walk through of all doors, windows, walls, floors, and ceilings in each live-in facility, to ensure that all areas are safe and in good repair to prevent injuries.  Deficiencies will be documented on the work ticket and repaired immediately.  A Preventive Maintenance recurring work ticket is being created that we can pull from the system to show the walk-throughs.  Beginning on Monday 8th the Sr. Director of Facilities and Food Service, and over the course of the next month (and monthly thereafter), will walk through each program building in Boerne and West Avenue to review all of the areas that need work and schedule work for the following day after the walk through. Photos of the repaired plexiglass was sent via email from the administrator. "
01/13/2021,748.507(1) - Individual Standards Evaluated,Individual Standards Evaluated,No,03/10/2021,03/17/2021,Individual Standards Evaluated,Medium High,Yes,A staff lacked boundaries with residents by horse playing with them. ,"A compliance response was received from the administrator. Covered in staff notes/meetings March 3-5th- Although TBRI encourages playful engagement, staff must ensure boundaries.  Playful engagement and horseplaying are two separate things.  We do not allow a lot of horseplay between residents, because it often escalates into physical altercations (residents dont often know when to stop or communicate they are not comfortable with the interaction). This is same for residents and staff.  Staff need to be mindful that playful engagement is used as an appropriate intervention/response to redirect low level behaviors.  Staff should never horseplay with residents."
01/04/2021,748.303(e)(3)(A) - Individual Standards Evaluated,Individual Standards Evaluated,No,03/17/2021,03/21/2021,Individual Standards Evaluated,Medium,Yes,Operation did not report to licensing timely when staff were diagnosed positive for COVID.,"Email states: It is important that the employee notifies the Senior Dir. Of Human Resources when learning of positive communicable disease test results (in this case COVID-19).  It's a function of the HR Department to document and track such reports, conduct contact tracing, notification of those potentially exposed, and finalize a return to work date with the employee based on onset of symptoms, currently symptomology, and/or doctors recommendations.  
 
It is the supervisors responsibility (Program Manager, Program Administrator, or a Senior Director) to ensure that an incident report is completed and the hotline is notified within 24 hours of the agency being made aware of the positive result.  The date, time, operators name & ID number, and the case reference number must be documented on the incident report.  The incident report will be maintained in the employees personnel record (paper or electronic copy).
 
The timeframe and documentation of notification piece was covered in staff notes for meetings held 
agency-wide on January 26 - 28th.  It was covered in more general terms.
 
The response above will be in staff notes for meetings held agency-wide on March 16 - 18th.  
